<section id="overview">
    <h2>Overview</h2>
    <p>Claude Shell is a macOS management console that lets you expose a running
    Claude Code CLI session to a remote browser through a tunnel provider.
    The desktop app discovers your local sessions, runs a local WebSocket
    proxy with an authentication token, and orchestrates a tunnel
    (ngrok, Microsoft Dev Tunnels, or Cloudflare Tunnel) so you—or a
    teammate—can drive the session from any browser.</p>

    <div class="note">
        <strong>Console only.</strong> Claude Shell does not interact with
        Claude itself. All prompts, tool approvals, and responses happen
        in the remote web client that connects through the tunnel.
    </div>
</section>

<section id="quickstart">
    <h2>Quick Start</h2>
    <ol class="steps">
        <li>Make sure the <code>claude</code> CLI is installed and reachable on
        your <code>PATH</code>.</li>
        <li>Open the <strong>Server</strong> tab and click
        <strong>Start Server</strong>. Claude Shell binds a local WebSocket
        on a random port and generates an auth token.</li>
        <li>Open the <strong>Tunnels</strong> tab, choose a provider from the
        dropdown, click <strong>Add</strong>, then press the green start
        icon next to the new row.</li>
        <li>When the status turns <em class="ok">connected</em>, copy the
        <strong>Public URL</strong> and share it together with the auth
        token (or the full <code>?token=…</code> URL) with the remote user.</li>
        <li>The remote user opens the URL in a browser, picks the discovered
        session in the sidebar, and starts working.</li>
    </ol>
    <div class="tip">
        <strong>Try it locally first.</strong> Use <strong>Open Test Client</strong>
        on the Server tab to launch the embedded web UI in your default
        browser with the token already filled in.
    </div>
</section>

<section id="sessions">
    <h2>Sessions Tab</h2>
    <p>Lists every Claude Code CLI session running on your machine.</p>
    <table>
        <tr><th>Column</th><th>Description</th></tr>
        <tr><td>PID</td><td>Process ID of the Claude CLI session.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Name</td><td>Session display name, or <code>(unnamed)</code>.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>CWD</td><td>Working directory the session was launched from.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Started</td><td>Local time the session began (DD/MM HH:MM).</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Status</td><td><em class="ok">alive</em> or <em class="bad">dead</em>.</td></tr>
    </table>
    <p>Click the refresh icon (or press <kbd>⌘R</kbd>) to rescan immediately.</p>
</section>

<section id="server">
    <h2>Server Tab</h2>
    <p>Controls the local WebSocket proxy that bridges remote clients to your
    Claude sessions.</p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Start Server / Stop Server</strong> — Toggles the proxy.
        When running, the header shows the bound port and the number of
        connected clients.</li>
        <li><strong>URL</strong> — Read-only field with the full
        <code>ws://localhost:PORT/ws?token=…</code> connection string.</li>
        <li><strong>Copy URL</strong> — Copies that string to the clipboard.</li>
        <li><strong>Open Test Client</strong> — Launches the embedded web UI
        in your default browser. On macOS, you can choose to always open
        in Safari.</li>
        <li><strong>Claude binary path</strong> — Auto-detected from
        <code>PATH</code>, but editable. The override is persisted across
        launches in <code>com.komsoft.claudeshell</code> preferences.</li>
    </ul>
</section>

<section id="tunnels">
    <h2>Tunnels Tab</h2>
    <p>Configure and manage public tunnels that expose the local server.</p>

    <h3>Adding a tunnel</h3>
    <ol>
        <li>Pick a provider in the dropdown — the badge shows whether it's
        installed and authenticated.</li>
        <li>The port defaults to the running server's port. Change it before
        starting the server if you need a different one.</li>
        <li>Click the <strong>+</strong> (Add) button to insert a row.</li>
        <li>Click the green play button on the row to start the tunnel.</li>
    </ol>

    <h3>Per-row controls</h3>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Start / Stop</strong> — Toggle the tunnel process.</li>
        <li><strong>Restart</strong> — Useful when a tunnel ends up in
        <em class="bad">failed</em> state.</li>
        <li><strong>Remove</strong> — Delete the tunnel row.</li>
        <li><strong>Details</strong> — Open a dialog with the live
        provider log and any error output.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Status colors</h3>
    <table>
        <tr><th>State</th><th>Meaning</th></tr>
        <tr><td><em>idle</em></td><td>Configured but not started.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><em>starting</em></td><td>Provider process spawned, waiting for URL.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><em class="ok">connected</em></td><td>Public URL is live.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><em class="bad">failed</em></td><td>Provider exited or is missing.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><em>stopped</em></td><td>Cleanly stopped by you.</td></tr>
    </table>

    <h3>Supported providers</h3>
    <table>
        <tr><th>Provider</th><th>Binary</th><th>Setup notes</th></tr>
        <tr><td>ngrok</td><td><code>ngrok</code></td>
            <td>Requires <code>ngrok config add-authtoken …</code>.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Microsoft Dev Tunnels</td><td><code>devtunnel</code></td>
            <td>Requires <code>devtunnel user login</code>.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Cloudflare Tunnel</td><td><code>cloudflared</code></td>
            <td>Quick tunnels work with no account.</td></tr>
    </table>
    <p>Click <strong>Setup guide</strong> next to the provider dropdown for
    install instructions.</p>
</section>

<section id="logs">
    <h2>Logs Tab</h2>
    <p>Color-coded application log: session discovery, proxy activity, tunnel
    state changes, and errors. Each line is formatted as
    <code>HH:MM:SS [LVL] message</code>.</p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>DBG</strong> — gray, internal diagnostics.</li>
        <li><strong>INF</strong> — black, normal events.</li>
        <li><strong>WRN</strong> — yellow, recoverable issues.</li>
        <li><strong>ERR</strong> — red, failures requiring attention.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Use <strong>Clear</strong> to wipe the buffer, <strong>Copy</strong>
    to put the full log on the clipboard, or <strong>Save</strong> to write
    it to a <code>.log</code> file.</p>
</section>

<section id="remote">
    <h2>Remote Web Client</h2>
    <p>The web UI served by the proxy is what your remote user actually
    interacts with.</p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Connection bar</strong> — WebSocket URL, token, role
        (Controller or Viewer), and Connect / Disconnect.</li>
        <li><strong>Sidebar</strong> — Discovered Claude sessions; click one
        to attach.</li>
        <li><strong>Chat area</strong> — Streaming responses, tool-use
        prompts, and a multi-line input. <kbd>Enter</kbd> sends,
        <kbd>Shift</kbd>+<kbd>Enter</kbd> inserts a newline.</li>
        <li><strong>Abort</strong> — Cancel the running response.</li>
        <li><strong>Status bar</strong> — Live connection / authentication
        state with auto-reconnect.</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Roles:</strong> the first <em>Controller</em> connection drives
    the session; additional connections are forced into <em>Viewer</em>
    (read-only) mode.</p>
</section>

<section id="cli">
    <h2>Command Line</h2>
    <p>Running <code>claude-shell</code> with arguments dispatches commands to
    the running instance over a Unix domain socket
    (<code>/tmp/claude-shell-$USER.sock</code>). If no instance is running
    you'll see <code>error: no running instance found</code>.</p>
    <table>
        <tr><th>Command</th><th>Description</th></tr>
        <tr><td><code>claude-shell</code></td><td>Launch the GUI (or focus an existing instance).</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>claude-shell status</code></td><td>Print server, client, session, and tunnel summary.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>claude-shell sessions</code></td><td>List discovered Claude sessions.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>claude-shell start [port]</code></td><td>Start the proxy server on an optional port.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>claude-shell stop</code></td><td>Stop the proxy server.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>claude-shell url</code></td><td>Print the WebSocket connection string (handy with <code>pbcopy</code>).</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>claude-shell tunnel &lt;provider&gt;</code></td><td>Start a tunnel for the running server.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>claude-shell show</code></td><td>Bring the main window to the front.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>claude-shell --version</code></td><td>Print version and build number.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>claude-shell --help</code></td><td>Print built-in help.</td></tr>
    </table>
</section>

<section id="menus">
    <h2>Menus &amp; Shortcuts</h2>
    <table>
        <tr><th>Menu Item</th><th>Shortcut</th><th>Action</th></tr>
        <tr><td>File &gt; Close Window</td><td><kbd>⌘W</kbd></td><td>Hide the main window (app stays in the menu bar).</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Session &gt; Refresh Sessions</td><td><kbd>⌘R</kbd></td><td>Rescan running Claude sessions.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Tunnel &gt; Stop All Tunnels</td><td>—</td><td>Terminate every active tunnel process.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Help &gt; Claude Shell Help</td><td><kbd>⌘?</kbd></td><td>Open this help book.</td></tr>
    </table>
</section>

<section id="security">
    <h2>Security</h2>
    <ul>
        <li>Each server instance generates a fresh 256-bit random auth token,
        base64url-encoded (~43 characters).</li>
        <li>Tokens are validated with constant-time comparison.</li>
        <li>Tunnel providers terminate TLS — your traffic to the public URL
        is encrypted.</li>
        <li>Only one Controller may attach to a session at a time; others
        connect as Viewers and cannot send input.</li>
        <li>Treat the connection string like a password — anyone with it can
        drive your Claude session for as long as the tunnel is up.</li>
    </ul>
    <div class="note">
        <strong>Stop tunnels when finished.</strong> The Tunnel menu's
        <em>Stop All Tunnels</em> action is the fastest way to revoke
        access.
    </div>
</section>

<section id="troubleshooting">
    <h2>Troubleshooting</h2>
    <table>
        <tr><th>Symptom</th><th>What to check</th></tr>
        <tr><td>No sessions appear</td>
            <td>Run <code>claude</code> in a terminal to confirm the CLI is
            installed; press <kbd>⌘R</kbd> to refresh.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Server fails to start</td>
            <td>Verify the <em>Claude binary path</em> on the Server tab.
            Check the Logs tab for the underlying error.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Provider shows ⊘ "not found"</td>
            <td>Install the provider's CLI (<code>brew install ngrok</code>,
            <code>brew install cloudflare/cloudflare/cloudflared</code>,
            or download <code>devtunnel</code> from Microsoft).</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Tunnel stuck on <em>starting</em></td>
            <td>Open <strong>Details</strong> for the row to read the
            provider's live log; auth tokens for ngrok or devtunnel may
            be missing.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Remote browser cannot connect</td>
            <td>Some networks block WebSockets. Try a different network,
            disable browser extensions, or check Screen Time / firewall
            rules.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Second launch does nothing</td>
            <td>Expected — Claude Shell is single-instance. The second
            invocation focuses the running window.</td></tr>
    </table>
</section>

<section id="requirements">
    <h2>System Requirements</h2>
    <ul>
        <li>macOS 13.0 (Ventura) or later</li>
        <li>Claude Code CLI on <code>PATH</code></li>
        <li>At least one tunnel provider:
            <code>ngrok</code>, <code>devtunnel</code>, or
            <code>cloudflared</code></li>
    </ul>
</section>

</main>

